      "round": 1,
      "round_explanation": "By round 1, players have a bit of information. Buffalo successfully traded away some RED for BLUE, learning that at least one counterpart is willing to take RED and give up BLUE at modestly favorable terms. Bear’s initial attempt to buy BLUE with GREEN was rejected, suggesting that BLUE is not cheap for others, or at least that their first rate looked unattractive. Goose’s attempt to buy GREEN with BLUE also failed, indicating others demand quite a bit for GREEN or view BLUE as valuable. Now Buffalo has more BLUE and less RED, Bear’s holdings are unchanged, and Goose has fewer BLUE and more RED. Buffalo might press their advantage, trying to sell remaining RED or excess BLUE in small, low-risk swaps. Bear, seeing BLUE is scarce, may sweeten offers or pivot to acquiring RED, which is somewhat cheaper. Goose, having given up BLUE earlier, may either seek to replenish BLUE cheaply or offload some now-surplus RED. All three remain cautious about making offers that are clearly loss-making for counterparts.",
