 them blue.\n\nEach proposer sees their own surplus calculator; responders see their own surplus when a proposal appears. So accept/decline choices are myopic and individually rational: players almost never accept a strictly negative-surplus trade, but might accept small positive trades even if they suspect the proposer is getting more. Proposers must also consider that if a trade is attractive to both potential partners, any accepting partner might be randomly chosen as recipient; the proposer cannot target a specific partner.\n\nGiven the short, three-round structure and the fixed proposer order, players have limited time to experiment. Early in the game they often test modest trades to learn how others react to different chip colors. Over time, they may infer that some chips are more or less valued by particular opponents (e.g., if Squid eagerly takes blue, others might infer Squid likes blue). However, with only nine total proposal turns, learning is partial. The likely overall pattern in this forecasted game is: early, exploratory proposals that are sometimes declined as too one-sided; then slightly more balanced offers that generate actual trades once players sense who is willing to move which colors. Because everyone can see their own surplus exactly, accepted trades are nearly always weakly beneficial to both proposer and recipient, but not necessarily surplus-maximizing from the analyst’s perspective.",
