  "game_explanation": "All three players start with 10 RED, 10 BLUE, and 10 GREEN chips. GREEN is common-value at $0.50 for everyone, so it is a neutral asset with no disagreement about its worth. The strategic tension centers on RED and BLUE, where private values differ.\n\nDog and Owl both value BLUE at $1.00 and RED at $0.80 and $0.30 respectively, while Mouse values BLUE at only $0.60 and RED at $0.20. This means Dog and Owl are relatively strong buyers of BLUE and weak buyers of RED, and Mouse is a relatively weak buyer of both colored chips but especially weak on RED. However, none of them know the others’ exact values; they only know the public value ranges and see their own calculator when contemplating trades. This uncertainty forces them to infer others’ valuations from observed acceptances and rejections.\n\nGiven the ranges ($0.10–$1.00 for RED and BLUE), each player knows that others might either value a chip more, less, or roughly the same as they do. This leads to cautious proposals early, often with small quantities and relatively favorable terms for the proposer, to probe willingness to trade. Because multiple responders may accept and one is randomly chosen, proposers cannot target a specific partner; they instead design trades that are profitable for themselves regardless of which counterpart accepts. As history unfolds, players update beliefs: e.g., if someone accepts an offer that is very bad from the proposer’s perspective, the proposer infers that partner probably values the requested color much more or the offered color much less.\n\nSurplus opportunities (from an analyst’s omniscient view) mainly exist when high-value BLUE owners trade with low-value BLUE owners, and when higher-value RED owners trade with lower-value RED owners. But because Dog and Owl both highly value BLUE and moderately/poorly value RED, while Mouse assigns low values to both RED and BLUE, most efficient gains would come from Mouse shedding BLUE and maybe accumulating some GREEN, while Dog and Owl might try to offload some RED if they guess that someone values it more.\n\nHowever, subjectively, each player sees only their own calculator and the public history. Dog and Owl see that BLUE is very valuable and RED is somewhat/weakly valuable, so they will be reluctant to give up BLUE and somewhat open to giving up RED if they can cheaply get BLUE or maybe GREEN in return. Mouse sees that BLUE and RED are both relatively low-value, so may be more willing to part with either if compensated with enough GREEN or with more chips overall. Throughout the three rounds, players face a tradeoff: accept immediate small gains from slightly favorable trades now, or hold out for potentially larger gains later at the risk that others might secure their own favorable positions or the game may end with unused surplus. Since there are exactly three rounds and each player gets one proposal per round, each player has three chances to propose but nine total opportunities to respond, creating a mix of active and reactive strategy.\n\nOverall, the likely bargaining dynamics are: small, probing offers in the early round; rejections of obviously loss-making trades according to private calculators; occasional accepted trades where the proposer leaves some surplus for counterparts (especially when testing the market); and mild belief updating across rounds as players react to what others accept or reject. Because of random recipient selection when multiple accept, proposals that are profitable against either potential partner are especially attractive, while extremely targeted proposals are risky because you cannot guarantee trading with the most favorable counterparty.",
